PART I: GENERAL INTRODUCTION: || PART III: Chromatic Shifting and Chroma-

System of Tuning the Violin.— Normal and
Tempered Finger Position. — Holding the
Violin and the Bow.—True Strings.—
EXERCISES.—The Open Strings.—Plac-
ing of the Fingers.—Tempering Intervals in
relation to an open String.—Formation of
Double-Stops. — 29 Duettinos for two
Violins.

PART II*: The Semitone and Tritone in the

‘tic Tone-succession. — The Augmented

Second. — Harmonic and Melodic Scales,
with Bowing Exercises for Legato, Martellato,
Staccato, Spiccato and Saltato.—Consonant
Chords.—Double-Stops of the Perfect
Fifth —The Broken Triad in a Variety of
Movement and Form.

Major Scales of G, C, F, Bb, D and Eb with || PART IV: Dissonant Chords.—The Dimin-

256 Rhythmical Exercises (110 with a
second Violin).

PART IIb: The Semitone and Tritone in A,

some BE, Db, B and G> Major, Twelve Major

Scales with Semitone and Tritone through

the Circle of Fifths, 12 Major Scales also

in Chromatic succession, with 395 Rhyth-
mical Exercises.

ished and Augmented Triad in Single Tones
and Double-Stops in various Keys, with
Changes of Bowing.—The Chord of the
Diminished and Dominant Seventh in Single
